# Connector Implementation Rules

## No hallucination — explore first

Before writing any connector code, you MUST:
1. Read the **existing entities** in `src/domain/entities.ts` to understand the exact shapes expected.
2. Read the **connector interface** in `src/connectors/types.ts` to know the method signatures.
3. Read the **service** that calls the connector (`src/services/startups.ts`, `boardBrief.ts`, `society.ts`) to understand what fields are actually consumed downstream.
4. If the real API structure is unknown, **call the API** (or read its official docs) to verify field names, pagination format, and auth before mapping.

Never invent field names, property keys, or API response shapes. Map only what the API actually returns.

## Mapping strategy

- Use **only fields that exist in `domain/entities.ts`** as output types.
- If an API field doesn't map cleanly, document the gap with a comment and use `undefined`.
- Prefer narrow property lists in API requests — only fetch what the connector interface needs.

## Error handling

```typescript
// ✅ Wrap every fetch in a try/catch and rethrow as ConnectorFailed
try {
  const res = await fetch(...);
  if (!res.ok) throw new Error(`HTTP ${res.status}`);
  return mapToEntity(await res.json());
} catch (err) {
  throw ConnectorFailed(`hubspot.listStartups failed`, { cause: String(err) });
}

// ❌ Never let raw fetch errors bubble up untyped
```

## Pagination

All list methods must exhaust pagination silently — callers receive the full set.
Use cursor/`after` (HubSpot), cursor (Drive), cursor (Monday items_page).

## Auth

- HubSpot: `Authorization: Bearer <token>` header, v3 CRM endpoints.
- Monday: `Authorization: <token>` header, single GraphQL endpoint `https://api.monday.com/v2`.
- Drive: Service account via `google-auth-library` JWT, scope `https://www.googleapis.com/auth/drive.readonly`.

Never hardcode credentials. Token/credentials come from `AppConfig.connectors` only.
